title: A Phase 2a, Randomized, Placebo-Controlled, Double-Blind, Crossover Study to Evaluate the Safety, Tolerability and Effects of CST-2032 and CST-107 on Cognition in Subjects With Mild Cognitive Impairment or Mild Dementia Due to Parkinson's or Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief: This is a Phase 2a, randomized, placebo-controlled, double-blind, crossover study to evaluate the effects CST-2032 administered with CST-107 on cognition in participants with Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI) or mild dementia.
description_detailed:
Approximately 60 participants will be enrolled in a 2 period, 2-way crossover design following study eligibility confirmation during the screening period. During each treatment period, subjects will receive daily doses of CST-2032 administered with CST-107 or matching placebo for 14 days. Each treatment period will be separated by a washout period of at least 7 days and up to 21 days.

All participants will complete clinical, cognitive and pharmacodynamic assessments during each treatment period. PK blood samples will be collected prior to, during and after study medication administration.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in DSST Score
outcomeMeasures.description: Change from Baseline in Digit Symbol Substitution Test (DSST) after CST-2032 co-administered with CST-107 compared to placebo. Participants are asked to copy simple graphic symbols that are paired to the digits 1-9 within a specified time period. Using a key, the examinee is asked to draw each symbol under its corresponding number. The examinee's score is determined by the number of symbols correctly drawn within a 90-second time limit. Higher scores indicate better performance.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: Full Analysis Set - All randomized participants who took at least 1 dose of blinded study drug (CST-2032 + CST-107 or placebo). Participants were analyzed according to the treatment assigned at randomization. It is noted that whilst all the above participants were included in the overall analysis, there were some participants for whom data was not available at individual timepoints and the resulting corrected number of participants analyzed is presented per parameter below.
outcomeMeasures.timeFrame: Change from Baseline after 7 and 14 days of treatment respectively.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline in CANTAB Adaptive Tracking Mean Level of Difficulty Achieved
outcomeMeasures.description: Measures changes in visual and motor coordination and vigilance. In this task, a small circle (target) continuously moves across the screen in a semi-randomized fashion, so as to minimize the subject's ability to predict the trajectory of the target. The subject is instructed to use his/her finger on the touch screen to move a small dot so that it is consistently within the center of the moving target on the screen. During the test, the speed of the circle is adjusted in response to the subject's ability to keep the dot in the circle, ensuring that the test is adapted to the individual subject. The outcome variable was the mean 'difficulty multiplier', which is a calculation adjustment of the participant's accuracy on target relative to current target speed, averaged over the entire testing session. The difficulty multiplier ranges from 0 to 10. Attainment of a higher difficulty multiplier indicates better performance.

explanation_target: Reason: The trial tests CST-2032 co‑administered with CST‑107 to evaluate effects on cognition (MCI / mild dementia), indicating a symptomatic cognitive‑improvement aim rather than targeting core AD pathology (amyloid/tau). CST‑2032 is described in company and literature sources as an oral, brain‑permeant β2‑adrenoceptor (β2‑AR) agonist intended to reactivate brain adrenergic function; CST‑107 is nadolol (a brain‑sparing β‑blocker) used to block peripheral β2 effects. citeturn0search5turn0search4turn1search1

Act: Key extracted details — Trial NCT05104463 (Phase 2a, randomized, placebo‑controlled, double‑blind, crossover) tested cognition with CST‑2032 + CST‑107 vs placebo; CST‑2032 is a β2‑AR agonist (small molecule) and CST‑107 is nadolol (beta blocker). Results/press reports describe rapid, domain‑specific cognitive improvements (memory, attention, executive function) rather than disease‑modifying biological effects on amyloid or tau. citeturn0search5turn0search4turn1search5

Reflect: Classification check — Because the mechanism is adrenergic stimulation to improve cognitive performance (symptomatic improvement) and both agents are small‑molecule drugs (CST‑2032 is a small‑molecule β2 agonist; CST‑107 is nadolol), the most appropriate category is 'cognitive enhancer' rather than a disease‑targeted biologic or disease‑targeted small molecule (which would target pathological processes like amyloid/tau) or a neuropsychiatric‑symptom intervention (which targets behavioral/psychiatric symptoms). No evidence in the cited materials indicates an amyloid- or tau‑targeting disease‑modifying mechanism. citeturn1search1turn0search4
explanation_agent: Reason: The intervention is a brain‑penetrant β2‑adrenoceptor (β2‑AR) agonist (CST‑2032) given with nadolol (CST‑107) to limit peripheral β effects, i.e., the mechanism is modulation of the adrenergic receptor (a neurotransmitter receptor) to produce symptomatic cognitive improvement rather than targeting amyloid, tau, inflammation, or other disease‑modifying pathways. citeturn0search0turn0search4

Act: Extracted details — Trial NCT05104463 (Phase 2a, randomized, placebo‑controlled, double‑blind, crossover) tested CST‑2032 (oral, brain‑penetrant β2‑AR agonist) co‑administered with CST‑107 (nadolol, brain‑sparing β‑blocker) for 14 days versus placebo, with cognitive outcomes reported (improvements in DSST and other cognitive measures reported in AD/PD presentation). These facts support classification under CADRO category D (Neurotransmitter Receptors). citeturn0search0turn0search4turn0search7

Reflect: This classification aligns with CADRO because the drugs act on adrenergic (β2) receptors — a canonical neurotransmitter receptor target — and the trial aims at symptomatic cognitive enhancement rather than modifying core AD pathologies (amyloid/tau). If future data show direct disease‑modifying effects (e.g., on amyloid or tau biology), reclassification could be considered. citeturn0search1turn0search4
